BURKHOLDERIA CEPACIA, POST-OPERATIVE BACTEREMIA - USA (NEW YORK)(02)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed, 9 Mar 2005
From: Knud Siboni <mksiboni@dadlnet.dk>

In 1977 we diagnosed 9 and 7 non-fatal cases of postoperative bacteremia
due to _Pseudomonas_ (now _Burkholderia_) _cepacia_ in Denmark [9 cases]
and the Netherlands [7 cases], from an intrinsically contaminated
anaesthetic. The intervals from operation to hyperpyrexia were 14-70 hours
and fever lasted 2-4 days, so the patient discussed in the previous
posting, febrile after 12 hours, has [probably] acquired his infection
during the operation and, as suggested, with a high inoculum.
Siboni K, et al: Scand J Inf Dis 1979; 11:39-45.
Borghans JGA, et al. Acta Path Microbiol Scand 1979; 87B:15-20.
--
K. Siboni, MD, D Med Sci
Emeritus Professor of Clinical Microbiology
Odense University Hospital
Odense, Denmark
<mksiboni@dadlnet.dk>
[ProMED thanks Dr. Siboni for his comments. - Mod.LL]
